	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1173602">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1173602">
                  
                  An ice version of Char could be a compromise among the two sides of that issue.  Turning Shocking Grasp into a dot that drains endurance would be innovative and not at all change the fact that a sorcerer primarily does damage through dds, in fact far and away this would still be the case.  It would be radically different from a typical dot and would actually suplement the idea of a fast paced battle unlike CV.  If the change made it still barely worth useing, well does anyone utilize it much currently anways?  Imagine starting the fight with an endurance draining, fast paced, high damaging Shocking Grasp that adds a new damage option for the class.  If anything it would seem to augment a CV based strategy compared to the other regular DDs.  Obviously when I talk about this I mean that you would need to race to snare or immobilize the opponent or risk rapid death.        <br />
<br />
Here is what the role of each caster seemed to be from the descriptions given:  <br />
<br />
<br />
Sorcerer:  Primary roles:  A great damage dealer with some nice damage variety/options, somewhat better than other casters at dealing damage (around mabey 15% from the less damage casters; depends partly on how pets are factored), very good at anti-magic and spell defense which should consist of great resist buffs, reflects, countershields, silence, and the sanctuary spells.  Secondary roles:  Rudimentary CC, some limited buffing capacity, and some utility. <br />
<br />
Psionicist:  Primary roles:  Good damage dealer, Powerful and best charm, best mesmerizes and CC; good at causing psionic effects on opponents.  Secondary roles:  Able to cast some spells that debilitate or debuff the enemy, somewhat advanced buffing compared to most casters, some other utility.  <br />
<br />
Druid:  Primary roles:  Nice damage, able to act as a backup healer and good buffs compared to most casters, good at rooting and controlling movement.  Seecondary roles:  Limited CC capacity, able to summon some creatures that help out during a fight, and some basic utility.  <br />
<br />
Necromancer:  Primary roles:  A good damage dealer (mostly through dots and lifetaps), great at summoning useful pets.  Secondary roles:  Crude CC ability, limited buffs, some ability to debilitate opponent and a dash of extra utility.     <br />
<br />
This would be partly situational as in certain cases a Sorcerer might be the most effective while in another a Psionicist, Druid, or Necromancer's abilities might push them ahead of the others.  <br />
<br />
Now the game comes quite close to fulfilling the above.  The main thing that I am saying is that it needs just a bit more refinement and polish to bring out the full potential.  None of this is redefining the sorcerer or anything, in fact it is that some people wish to redefine the other casters into some new form.  The uniqueness and creativity of clerics and shamans is good to look at in terms of flavoring.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
