	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_1173852">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1173852">
                  
                  <div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>Originally Posted by <strong>jhorry</strong></div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">
Also, as seen in eq1, if certain classes are considered &quot;the best&quot;, then contient will be designed to match their potiential, not the potiential of a class that is under them, so these could further hinder the functionality of the classes that are deamed &quot;hybrids&quot; or what have you.<br />
<br />
<br />
Its like this with the healers, tanks, and offensive fighters currently. They dont want their to be a &quot;best&quot; choice for their shared Job, but they want each class to have different ways of achieving this Job.<br />
<br />
I mean just look at the healers.<br />
<br />
Cleric: Melee oriented healer, rewarded for being in the fray by an enery returning attack and ally buffs.<br />
<br />
Disciple: Melee oriented healer, rewarded for stringing attacks together differently, and keeping allies / foes buffed /debuffed with bonds, working with their Jin pool.<br />
<br />
Bloodmage: Spell dps oriented healer, rewarded for damaging foes, keeping range, and modulating health/energy/endurance.<br />
<br />
Shaman: melee and spell oriented healer, depending on your totem it either rewards keeping your distance and casting or getting in the fray, weakens enemies very well.<br />
<br />
<br />
When you compare their healing potinetial, they are all roughly the same in the long run, with slight advantages in different situations, but you have 4 very highly diverse gameplay choices.<br />
<br />
In my opinion, this is one of the reasons healers are played so much currently, because you can be a Tank, melee dps, spelll dps, or a mix of those while still being a healer.<br />
<br />
<br />
Problem with casters is that since their shared Job is NOT balanced, if you chose anything other than sorcerer you are sacroficing your main job for *potientially* useful sub roles, while if you choose sorcerer currently, you pretty much dont have a useful sub role.<br />
<br />
What i find truely odd is the sorcerers can CC as well as Psionicists in some contient, yet i dont see psionicists ever reaching near a sorcerer's dps in any senerio...<br />
<br />
Just things like that a year down the road will start to really bog the game down in terms of enjoyability.<br />
<br />
Players should never have to choose between being &quot;functional&quot; and playing what they personally find fun.<br />
<br />
<br />
EDIT: As a side note, i think it is completely rediculous that they are considering AA's when classes arent finished or balanced yet! lol, a year down the road sure, but let things settle into place first!</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>
<br />
It seems that the healers might have been the best implemented  archetype going by the sort of uniqueness, creativity, and balance that exists among them.  It is interesting to note that half of them have specializations while none of the arcane casters do.  This wouldn't be nearly as much of a problem if every class had one of the traits:  concentrations/forms, stances, specializations, ability points, or something unique like that.  I find the Shaman, Cleric, Bloodmage, and Necromancer to be particularly well endowed in this regard.  The psionicist's five concentrations are nifty as well.  It is quite impressive to see the three Shaman forms as with the very intriuging phoenix.  This is a primarily a matter of flavor however no game can overlook the subjective yet pervasive importance of such advances and factors.       <br />
<br />
You are definitely right that no class was meant to be a totally &quot;pure&quot; class with only one role and no sub-role options/capacities.  This does not contradict possessing a speciality or class uniqueness; it just means avoiding the primitive one-dimensionality of so many previous games.
                  
		</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
